          <worked_example>
            <title>Colours of light</title>
            <question>
              <para>A photon of wavelength <unit_number><number>500</number><unit>nm</unit></unit_number> is emitted by a traffic light.</para>
              <list list-type="enumerated">
                <item>
                  <para>What is the energy of the photon?</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <para>What is the frequency of the photon?</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <para>Use <link target-id="t:Optic:Colours"/> to determine the colour of the light.</para>
                </item>
              </list>
            </question>
            <answer>
              <workstep>
                <title>What information is given and what do we need to find?</title>
                <para>We are given <latex>\lambda = <unit_number><number><coeff>500</coeff><exp>-9</exp></number><unit>m</unit></unit_number></latex> and we need to find the photon's <emphasis effect="italics">energy</emphasis>, <emphasis effect="italics">frequency</emphasis> and <emphasis effect="italics">colour</emphasis>.</para>
              </workstep>
              <workstep>
                <title>Use the equation <latex>E=\frac{hc}{\lambda }</latex> to find the photon's energy</title>
                <latex display="block">
		\begin{align}
		 E&amp; = \frac{hc}{\lambda }\\
		 &amp; = \frac{\left(<number><coeff>6.63</coeff><exp>-34</exp></number>\right)\times \left(<number><coeff>3</coeff><exp>8</exp></number>\right)}{<number><coeff>500</coeff><exp>-9</exp></number>}\\
		 &amp; = <unit_number><number><coeff>3.98</coeff><exp>-19</exp></number><unit>J</unit></unit_number>
		\end{align}
		</latex>
                

                <para>The energy of the photon is <unit_number><number><coeff>3.98</coeff><exp>-19</exp></number><unit>J</unit></unit_number>.</para>
              </workstep>
              <workstep>
                <title>We know the energy of the photon, now we can use <latex>E=hf</latex> to solve for the frequency</title>
                <latex display="block">
		\begin{align}
		 E&amp; = hf\\
		  f&amp; = \frac{E}{h}\\
		 &amp; = \frac{<number><coeff>3.98</coeff><exp>-19</exp></number>}{<number><coeff>6.63</coeff><exp>-34</exp></number>}\\
		 &amp; = <unit_number><number><coeff>6.00</coeff><exp>14</exp></number><unit>Hz</unit></unit_number>
		\end{align}
		</latex>
                

                <para>The frequency of the photon is <unit_number><number><coeff>6</coeff><exp>14</exp></number><unit>Hz</unit></unit_number>.</para>
              </workstep>
              <workstep>
                <title>Use the table to find the colour of light</title>
                <para>The wavelength given in the question is <unit_number><number>500</number><unit>nm</unit></unit_number>. We can see in the table that green light has wavelengths between <number>492</number> – <unit_number><number>577</number><unit>nm</unit></unit_number>. Therefore <unit_number><number>500</number><unit>nm</unit></unit_number> is in this range so the colour of the light is <emphasis effect="bold">green</emphasis>.</para>
              </workstep>
            </answer>
          </worked_example>
