<shortcode>01nb</shortcode>
<problem>
          <para>Will ultraviolet light with a wavelength of <unit_number><number>990</number><unit>nm</unit></unit_number> be able to emit electrons from a sheet of calcium with a work function of <unit_number><number>2.9</number><unit>eV</unit></unit_number>?</para>
        </problem>
        <solution url="TODO">
			  <para>We first calculate the energy of the photons:</para>
			  <latex display="block">
				\begin{align}
				E &amp; =  \frac{hc}{\lambda}\\
				  &amp; =  \frac{(<number><coeff>3</coeff><exp>8</exp></number>)(<number><coeff>6.63</coeff><exp>-34</exp></number>)}{<number><coeff>400</coeff><exp>-9</exp></number>}\\
					&amp; =  <unit_number><number><coeff>2.01</coeff><exp>-19</exp></number><unit>J</unit></unit_number>
				\end{align}
			  </latex>
			  <para>Next convert the work function energy into J:</para>
			  <latex display="block">
				\begin{align}
				  <number>2.9</number> \times <number><coeff>1.6</coeff><exp>-19</exp></number> = <unit_number><number><coeff>4.64</coeff><exp>-19</exp></number><unit>J</unit></unit_number>
				\end{align}
			  </latex>
			  <para>The energy of the photons is less than the work function of calcium and so no electrons will be emitted.</para>
			</solution>
            <correct />
